---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Prof. Stanley Oliver | Brenkley Doctoral College" description="Profile of Prof. Stanley Oliver, Director of Brenkley Doctoral College and doctoral supervisor in management strategy and organisational leadership.">

  <section class="py-16 px-6">
    <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">

      <a href="/supervisors" class="text-accent hover:underline text-sm mb-8 inline-block">&larr; Back to Supervisors</a>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-12">

        <!-- Sidebar -->
        <div class="md:col-span-1">
          <div class="card mb-6">
            <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-1">Prof. Stanley Oliver</h1>
            <p class="text-accent font-medium mb-4">Principal</p>
            <div class="space-y-2 text-sm text-muted">
              <p><strong class="text-foreground">Specialisms:</strong> Management Strategy, Organisational Leadership, Strategic Decision-Making</p>
              <p><strong class="text-foreground">Methods:</strong> Mixed methods (quantitative and qualitative)</p>
              <p><strong class="text-foreground">Active researchers:</strong> 6</p>
              <p><strong class="text-foreground">Capacity:</strong> Limited — please enquire</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="card mb-6">
            <h2 class="font-bold mb-3">Research Interests</h2>
            <ul class="text-sm text-muted space-y-2">
              <li>Strategic decision-making in complex organisations</li>
              <li>Executive leadership and board governance</li>
              <li>Organisational sensemaking under uncertainty</li>
              <li>Practitioner-research methodology</li>
              <li>Management education and executive development</li>
              <li>Strategic management in regulated industries</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="card">
            <h2 class="font-bold mb-3">Qualifications</h2>
            <ul class="text-sm text-muted space-y-2">
              <li>PhD, Management Studies, University of Warwick</li>
              <li>MBA, London Business School</li>
              <li>BA (Hons) Economics, University of Edinburgh</li>
              <li>Fellow, Chartered Management Institute</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Main content -->
        <div class="md:col-span-2 space-y-8">

          <div>
            <p class="section-label mb-3">Biography</p>
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">About Stanley</h2>
            <div class="space-y-4 text-muted">
              <p>Professor Stanley Oliver is the founding Director of Brenkley Doctoral College. His career spans academic research, executive education, and senior consultancy across the private, public, and third sectors. Before establishing Brenkley Doctoral College, he held positions at two UK business schools and served as a non-executive director for a major housing association and a national charity.</p>
              <p>Stanley's academic work centres on strategic decision-making — specifically, how leaders in complex, multi-stakeholder organisations make and communicate high-stakes decisions under conditions of genuine uncertainty. His research draws on theories of organisational sensemaking, principal-agent relationships, and strategic cognition, and his empirical work has spanned financial services, healthcare, higher education, and public sector contexts.</p>
              <p>He is a committed advocate for practitioner-research as a distinct and valuable form of scholarly inquiry. His view — developed through supervision of over thirty doctoral researchers to completion — is that the most important management research questions are often held by people inside organisations, and that the practitioner-researcher has a structural advantage in addressing them that the academic researcher cannot replicate.</p>
              <p>At Brenkley Doctoral College, Stanley provides strategic leadership, sits on the Academic Board, chairs the Admissions Committee, and maintains an active supervision portfolio. He speaks regularly at conferences on doctoral education, practitioner research, and the future of management knowledge.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6">Selected Publications</h2>
            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div class="card">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-foreground mb-1">Oliver, S. (2024). Strategic sensemaking in regulated industries: Evidence from three sector case studies. <em>Journal of Management Studies</em>, 61(4), 892–917.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-muted">An examination of how senior leaders in healthcare, financial services, and higher education construct and communicate strategic narratives under conditions of regulatory uncertainty.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="card">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-foreground mb-1">Oliver, S. (2023). The practitioner-researcher at doctoral level: Identity, positioning, and the politics of insider knowledge. <em>Management Learning</em>, 54(2), 145–163.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-muted">A theoretical and empirical exploration of the distinctive challenges and advantages facing professional executives undertaking doctoral research within their own organisational contexts.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="card">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-foreground mb-1">Oliver, S. &amp; Salimi, Z. (2022). Doctoral education for working professionals: Quality assurance in a flexible delivery context. <em>Quality in Higher Education</em>, 28(3), 312–329.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-muted">A co-authored examination of the quality assurance frameworks appropriate for non-traditional doctoral delivery, drawing on Brenkley Doctoral College's own model and comparative case analysis.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="card">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-foreground mb-1">Oliver, S. (2021). Executive decision-making and the role of evidence: A mixed methods study. <em>British Journal of Management</em>, 32(1), 78–99.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-muted">Drawing on interviews and document analysis with twenty-six senior executives across four sectors, this article examines the conditions under which executives engage with formal evidence in high-stakes decisions.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="card">
                <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-foreground mb-1">Oliver, S. (2019). <em>Management Research for Practitioners: A Guide to Rigorous Professional Inquiry.</em> London: Sage Publications.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-muted">A textbook for practitioner-researchers undertaking doctoral study, covering research design, methodology, writing, and the ethics of insider research. Now in its second edition.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Current Researchers</h2>
            <p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm">Prof. Oliver currently supervises six doctoral researchers across the Extended Advanced Diploma and Online PhD programmes. Research areas include AI governance in financial services, board leadership in NHS Trusts, strategic leadership in further education, and knowledge management in professional services firms.</p>
            <div class="card">
              <p class="text-sm text-muted">Interested in working with Prof. Oliver? Supervisory capacity is currently limited. Please contact our admissions team to discuss your research interests and assess fit before applying.</p>
              <div class="mt-4">
                <a href="/connect" class="btn-primary text-sm">Enquire about supervision</a>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>
